# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: augustana-college-illinois
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] Carlson was born the son of Carl Jacobson and Hedvig Andersdotter in Svarteborg, in Västra Götaland County, Sweden.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] He graduated from Augustana College in Rock Island, Illinois, (BA, 1898)(MS, 1899).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] He received a doctorate in physiology at Stanford in 1902 and began working at the University of Chicago in 1904.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] While Carlson was at Chicago, he conducted experiments on Fred Vlcek, similar to those conducted on Alexis St.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] Martin by William Beaumont, regarding his gastric fistula.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] These included illuminating his stomach with electric lights in order to observe digestion.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] Carlson became chairman of the physiology department at the University of Chicago in 1916 and remained chairman until 1940.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] Carlson was elected to the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1920 and the American Philosophical Society in 1928.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] He was president of the American Physiological Society from 1923 to 1925, and president of the AAAS in 1944.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] Carlson was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences in 1929.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] The cover story of the February 10, 1941, issue of *Time* magazine was devoted to Carlson's success as a teacher and his comparative studies of the muscular action of the heart in humans and the horseshoe crab.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/a-j-carlson] Carlson was one of 34 original signers of the Humanist Manifesto and in 1953 he was the first person to receive the American Humanist Association's Humanist of the Year award.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The college was founded in 1889 as **Decatur Female Seminary** by Presbyterian minister Frank Henry Gaines.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] In 1890, the name was changed to **Agnes Scott Institute** to honor the mother of the college's primary benefactor, Col.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The name was changed again to Agnes Scott College in 1906 and remains today a women's college.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is considered the first higher education institution in the state of Georgia to receive regional accreditation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The ninth and current president since July 2018 is Leocadia I.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Zak, who previously worked as director of the U.S.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] On July 27, 1994, the campus was listed on the National Register of Historic Places as part of the *South Candler Street-Agnes Scott College Historic District*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The historic district boundaries are East College Ave., South McDonough St., S.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Candler St., East Hill St. and East Davis St.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] It includes the entire campus, as well as historic homes adjacent to the campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The campus is also designated by the City of Decatur as a historic district.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The Reverend Frank Henry Gaines served as the first President of Agnes Scott, formally known as Decatur Female Seminary School, for 27 years (1896–1923).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] During his 27-year presidency, he ensured stability and success for the school, including the transition to the collegiate level, accreditation by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools, acquisition of 20 acres of land and 21 buildings and an increase in assets from $5,000 to $1.5 million.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott College is located within walking distance of downtown Decatur.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] It is served by Decatur station on the MARTA rail system, which is also a hub for buses, allowing students to travel to the greater Atlanta area.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott occupies more than 90 acres (360,000 m2) in Decatur.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The college also owns the Avery Glen apartments as well as more than a dozen houses in the surrounding neighborhoods housing faculty, staff, and students.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] There are also six dedicated undergraduate dormitories located on campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] American poet Robert Frost was first invited to speak at Agnes Scott in 1935, by English professor Emma May Laney, and he visited the college every winter from 1945 until his death in 1963.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] During his visits, he would read poetry in Presser Hall.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] A statue of the poet sculpted by George W.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] A collection of Robert Frost's poetry and letters can be viewed on the second floor of the McCain Library.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, named after Agnes Irvine Scott, is located at the center of "the main loop" and is a one among many Agnes Scott buildings that was listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Main was built in 1891, making it the oldest building on campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] This is documented in the history of Agnes Scott by McNair titled *Lest We Forget* published in 1983.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] As technology became more advanced so did Main.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Main Hall was the first building on campus and in the neighborhood to have electric lighting.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Some say that people would gather outside of Main at night just to admire the light shining within the building.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1891, the Gazebo at Agnes Scott college has served a multitude of purposes throughout the years.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] It was originally located in front of Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, however in 1926 it was moved to the west end of Rebekah Scott Hall.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The gazebo has been used as an office, meeting room, meditation chapel, and the Day Student Hut.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1906, Rebekah Scott Hall is the second oldest building remaining at Agnes Scott College.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Rebekah Scott Hall cost $70,000 to build.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] It is named after George Washington Scott's wife, Rebekah Butcher Scott.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The first floor of Rebekah Scott Hall contains offices, the office of financial aid, and the office of admissions.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The second and third floors are used as student housing.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Inman Hall, known commonly as Inman Hall, was built in 1911 and is the oldest building at Agnes Scott College which is used exclusively for student housing.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] In 1985, Inman had major renovations and the third floor was converted into study spaces for students.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] It is made from Indiana limestone and is three stories high.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The building faces west and has a large veranda which stretches along the front of the building.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Jennie D, Inman Hall was gifted to Agnes Scott College by Samuel.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1923, the Anna Young Alumnae House is dedicated to former science professor and Agnes Scott alumnae, Anna Irwin Young.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Originally the Alumnae House was a central gathering place for ASC alumnae.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The house and bedrooms are now used as a campus guest house.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Behind the house is the Alumnae Garden which houses a statue honoring Robert Frost.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The Anna Young Alumnae House underwent renovations from 2005 until 2009, after which it was re-opened.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The Bradley Observatory at Agnes Scott houses the Beck Telescope, a 30-inch (760 mm) Cassegrain reflector, as well as a planetarium with 70-seat capacity and a radio telescope.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Recently Agnes Scott College and the Georgia Tech Research Institute have collaborated on a project that added a LIDAR facility to the observatory.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The college's science building, the Bullock Science Center, contains a three-story rendering of part of the nucleotide sequence from Agnes Scott's mitochondrial DNA.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The DNA came from a blood sample of an ASC alumna who is a direct descendant of the college's namesake.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott has committed to becoming a carbon-neutral institute by the college's 150th anniversary in 2039 and has taken steps such as partnering with the Clean Air Campaign to reduce its impact on the local environment.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] As of 2015, the college has five solar arrays, four of which are part of Georgia Power's Advanced Solar Initiative.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The fifth array is on the rooftop of the Bradley Observatory and is also used for student research.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The renovation of Campbell Hall into a mixed-use residence hall, learning center, and office space was concluded in 2014 and included installation of a hydro-geothermic HVAC system.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott offers 34 undergraduate majors and 9 graduate and post-baccalaureate programs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The undergraduate core curriculum SUMMIT focuses on leadership development, global learning, and digital literacy.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] In 2019, Agnes Scott received the Heiskell Award for Scholars as Drivers of Innovation for its SUMMIT curriculum.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Undergraduate students are able to cross-register in other ARCHE member institutions.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The library at Agnes Scott College was an original Carnegie library built in 1910.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] A new library was authorized by the board of trustees in 1935 and opened in the fall of 1936.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] This new library was called the "Carnegie Library" and the original library was turned into a student center.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] It was renamed in 1951 for James McCain, on the occasion of his retirement as the 2nd President of the college.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] As of fall 2025, the student body consists of over 900 undergraduate and graduate students.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Approximately 60% of undergraduates that year were from Georgia.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Given Agnes Scott's emphasis on "mak[ing] lifelong friends, shar[ing] unforgettable experiences, discover[ing] meaningful places and find[ing] belonging in [their] community," a majority of students are encouraged to live on campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Thus, most students are expected to live in on-campus housing for all four years as an undergraduate at Agnes Scott College.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] However, the proportion of commuter students has increased (from 15.6 to 18.0 percent between the 2014–2015 and 2019–2020 academic year) due to limited housing caused from an increase in the student population (from 849 to 986 total students) and renovations to the residence halls.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] There are six resident halls situated around the Northern edge of the campus: Winship, Walters, Inman, Rebekah, Campbell, and Agnes Scott Hall (nicknamed "Main").
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] There are over 60 student organizations on campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The college hosts several student publications, including *The Silhouette*, the college's yearbook published annually, and *The Aurora*, Agnes Scott's literary magazine, and *The Profile*, Agnes Scott newspaper.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] All students are invited to join the staff.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division III which fields six sports teams including basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] All teams compete in the Collegiate Conference of the South (CCS).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott was named as one of the Colleges That Change Lives (CTCL).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The campus has been a filming location for many productions, including the filming location for Windsor College in Scream 2, with its campus standing in for the fictional university where Sidney Prescott enrolls to escape her past.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/agnes-scott-college] The college's Gothic architecture, particularly the main hall, provided the backdrop for many scenes, including the gazebo where a key reunion takes place.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] On March 23, 1835, Methodist settlers in Spring Arbor Township obtained a charter for a new seminary from the Michigan Territorial Legislature.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Construction began in 1837 outside Spring Arbor but the Panic of 1837 ended the project.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] A petition to move the seminary to Albion was approved by the legislature in 1839.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Sixty acres (243,000 m2) of land were donated by Jesse Crowell to the renamed "Wesleyan Seminary", and construction began in 1841.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The first classes were held in 1843 in the local Methodist Church.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] In 1844, classes began in the newly constructed Central Building, rebuilt as the present Robinson Hall in 1907.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The "Albion Female Collegiate Institute", founded in 1850, merged in 1857 under the name "The Wesleyan Seminary and Female College at Albion"; the merger was finalized in 1861, under the name "Albion College".
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The legislature authorized the college to confer full four-year college degrees upon both men and women that same year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion offers bachelor's degrees in business, the humanities, fine arts, natural sciences, and social sciences.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] It provides study-abroad programs in Europe, Latin America, Israel, Africa, Asia, and Australia.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion is perhaps best known for its equestrian center, the Nancy G.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Held Equestrian Center, and its biology and physical education programs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The three popular first majors, by number of 2021 graduates, were Biology/Biological Sciences (43), Economics (33), and Communication (28).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The 144-acre (0.58 km2) Whitehouse Nature Center at Albion works with public schools and the community.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] It features six miles of trails, 400 plant species, almost 170 bird species, 25 acres of oak-hickory and flood-plain forest, a tall-grass prairie and spring in the Adele D.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Whitehouse Wildflower Garden, an arboretum of Michigan trees and shrubs, 34 acres of farmland and research projects, and an interpretative building.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion College Astronomical Observatory was built in 1883-84 with encouragement from Samuel Dickie, later the college president.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Since 1990 one student went on to be a Rhodes Scholar, three were Goldwater Scholars, four Truman Scholars and seventeen Fulbright Scholars.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion College is home to the Prentiss M.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Brown Honors Center & Astronomical Observatory, named after Prentiss M.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Representative who graduated from Albion College in 1911.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The observatory is recognized as a Michigan State Historical Site and is used for both educational purposes and public viewing events, allowing students and community members to observe celestial objects such as planets, stars, and solar events.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] One of the notable features of the observatory is the 8.25" Alvan Clark Telescope, which dates back to the late 19th century.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Alvan Clark & Sons were renowned telescope makers and the presence of this telescope adds historical and educational value to the observatory.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] According to "Old Albion", a college history published in 1909, Alvan Clark himself crafted the Albion telescope, marking it as the last telescope he made before his death.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Although this claim remains unverified, Clark's health was declining in the early 1880s and the extent of his work in the years leading up to his death in 1887 is not well-documented.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] As of 2021 Fall enrollment, the student body was 53% female and 47% male.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] 73% of students were Michigan residents, 26% from out-of-state, and 1% from foreign countries.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Ninety-eight percent of students are enrolled full-time.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Prior to the 2010s the enrollment was heavily white and non-low income.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The numbers of black and Hispanic students increased, along with those of first-time university students and lower income students, due to a drive to increase and diversify enrollment.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Between 2013 and 2020, Albion increased its minority enrollment from 18% to 41%, and 48% of the incoming class in 2020 identified as persons of color.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The total cost of attending Albion full time as of 2022 was $67,310.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion offers financial aid of some form to 100% of its students.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The average financial aid package as of December 2022 was $53,714 per student.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion College is home to six social fraternities and as many sororities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] All are members of the North American Interfraternity Conference and all comprise Albion College's InterFraternity Council (IFC).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The song "Sweetheart of Sigma Chi" was written in 1911 by Byron D.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Dudleigh Vernor (Albion, 1914), and first performed by Harry Clifford (Albion, 1911) while undergraduates at Albion College.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion College is also home to fifteen honorary, professional, service, and special interest fraternities, including Phi Beta Kappa, established as the Michigan Beta chapter in 1940.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion athletics teams are nicknamed the *Britons*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The college is a member of the Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association (MIAA).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion has overall won 173 men's MIAA titles (tied for 2nd overall), as well as 26 women's MIAA titles (5th overall).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] Albion football won the NCAA Division III national championship in 1994.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albion-college] The esports team started in the 2021-2022 academic year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright College traces its founding to 1856 when "Union Seminary" opened.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Present-day Albright was formed by the mergers of several institutions: Albright Collegiate Institute, Central Pennsylvania College, and Schuylkill College.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] "Albright Collegiate Institute" opened in 1895 and was renamed Albright College three years later.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] "Union Seminary", meanwhile, became "Central Pennsylvania College" in 1887 and merged with Albright College in 1902.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] "Schuylkill Seminary", the third institution, was founded in 1881, became "Schuylkill College" in 1923, and merged into Albright in 1928.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright's campus relocated from Myerstown, to Schuylkill College's campus, which is the present location of Albright, at the base of Mount Penn in Reading.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The college is named for Pennsylvania-German evangelical preacher Jacob Albright, who founded the Evangelical Association (later known as the Evangelical United Brethren Church).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Born in 1759 in Douglass Township, (now Montgomery County) with the given name of Johannes Jacob Albrecht, the family changed their surname to "Albright" following Jacob's 1808 death.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In the late 2010s, enrollment began to decline at the college.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] By 2023, enrollment had declined to 1,652 students, a decline of nearly one-third from what it was in 2010.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] This had significant financial implications for the college which had a $20.3 million deficit in 2023.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In response, the college laid off 53 employees between 2022 and 2024.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In late 2024, the college also requested permission to draw a $25 million loan from its $53.1 million dollar endowment.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Shortly thereafter, the college's interim president announced plans to cut two degree programs but also launch several new programs and athletic teams.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In 2025, the college fired the staff of the Freedman Gallery and sold off the gallery's art collection, including works by Romare Bearden, Elizabeth Catlett, Salvador Dalí, Jasper Johns, Jacob Lawrence, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The move prompted outrage by Albright donors and museum professionals, especially since the sale would do little to help Albright's budgetary problems.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright College students are encouraged to cross and combine areas of study without taking longer to graduate.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The college offers Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science degrees, as well as a Master of Arts and Master of Science degrees in education.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The college also offers online and accelerated degree programs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright offers a wide range of classical and pre-professional programs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] It created one of the first undergraduate psychobiology programs in the nation in the 1960s.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The college's liberal arts curriculum has a cross-program focus that allows students to create an individualized education.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Fully half of Albright students have concentrations that combine two or three fields of learning.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The theatre program has been honored by the Kennedy Center American College Theater Festival consistently for many years.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] At the National Conference held every April in Washington DC, Albright's theatre program has garnered dozens of awards for distinguished work in performance, direction, dramaturgy, scenic, sound, costume, and lighting design.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Acclaimed productions of "Waiting for Godot" (2007), "Clybourne Park" (2016), "A Raisin in the Sun" (2018) have also been named "Outstanding Production of a Play" – recognizing them as the best college production of their years.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] "A Raisin in the Sun" also received eight other national awards, for distinguished performance, scenic and lighting design, director and performances.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The Albright Creative Research Experience (ACRE) is a multi-disciplinary program that affords undergraduate students the opportunity to conduct research or pursue creative endeavors during the three-week January Interim or summer break.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The students, who work one-on-one with faculty members, can be from any discipline, from STEM subjects to the humanities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In 2017, Albright College was named one of the "Best Northeastern" schools by The Princeton Review; this was the fourteenth consecutive year that the college was included in that category.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] News & World Report* ranked the college tied at #146 out of 211 in National Liberal Arts Colleges and tied at #31 in Top Performers on Social Mobility.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] News* ranked Albright 33rd out of 208 national liberal arts colleges in the "Campus Ethnic Diversity" category, and in the "Economic Diversity" category, Albright ranked 27th out of 210 national liberal arts schools.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] *The Economist* magazine listed Albright among the top 50 American colleges and universities for economic value in 2015.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright College athletic teams compete in the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division III as a member of the Middle Atlantic Conferences.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Charles "Pop" Kelchner founded the men's basketball team in 1900 and was athletic director at Albright College for 21 years.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] He was involved in aspects of Major League Baseball for over 50 years.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright College dedicated the baseball field as Kelchner Field in 1952.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Branch Rickey gave the dedication speech, with Connie Mack in attendance.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Kelchner was a graduate of Lafayette College with two degrees and was proficient in German, French, Italian, Spanish, Classical Latin and Greek.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] He served as Professor of Languages and athletic director.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Doggie Julian was the head football coach at Albright from 1929 to 1930.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Biggie Munn was the head football coach at Albright College from 1935 to 1936, before coaching Syracuse University (1946), and most notably Michigan State College (1947–1953), where his 1952 squad won a national championship.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] William "Lone Star" Dietz was the director of athletics and head football coach at Albright from 1937 to 1942.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Dietz led the football team to their first undefeated season in 1937.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] He previously led Washington State to 1916 Rose Bowl victory.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In the National Football League, Dietz had coached the Boston "Redskins" (1933–1934), the forerunner of the Washington Commanders.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Dietz is in the Albright College Athletic Hall of Fame and the College Football Hall of Fame.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] In 1948, the University of Maryland Eastern Shore (UMES) and Albright College played the first intercollegiate football game between an Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCU) institution and a majority-white institution.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The Philadelphia Eagles held preseason training camp at Albright from 1968 through 1972.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Renken was athletic director and basketball head coach for 38 consecutive seasons.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] A highly regarded figure in collegiate athletics in general and specifically basketball, Renken was the president of the United States Olympic Basketball Team Selection Committee for the 1976 Olympic Games.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] He also served as the president of the National Association of Basketball Coaches (NABC) in 1979–1980.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Durante, however, declined reinstatement, citing his former teammates' stated lack of trust in him.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] Albright's campus radio station, WXAC 91.3 FM is a student-operated college radio station.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] The initial call name was WALC, but was later changed to WXAC on March 8, 1965.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/albright-college] WALC had been the same call name for the Alcoa Steamship Lines.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo was established in the 1850s when the Great Western Railroad was extended to that point.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] It was briefly named "DeSoto", after Hernando de Soto, until the discovery of an identically named village in Jackson County.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Thompson who, reportedly, saw the name Aledo (a municipality in Spain) in Webster's Dictionary.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Development began in the 1850s, and the oldest surviving buildings date from the following decade.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] A post office has been in operation at Aledo since September 24, 1856.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] In 1857, the county seat was moved to Aledo from Millersburg after a countywide referendum.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo was incorporated on August 15, 1863.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] In the 1950s, the first Tastee-Freez in the United States was built in the downtown.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The Downtown Aledo Historic District was established in 2016, with 75 contributing historic buildings in the downtown area.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo is located in central Mercer County.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Illinois Route 17 passes through the city center on Third Street, leading east 8 miles (13 km) to Viola and west 14 miles (23 km) to New Boston on the Mississippi River.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Illinois Route 94 follows IL 17 along Southeast Third Street turns south at the city center onto South College Avenue.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] IL 94 leads south-southwest 29 miles (47 km) to Biggsville and northeast 22 miles (35 km) to U.S.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Route 67 on the southern outskirts of the Quad Cities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Census Bureau, Aledo has a total area of 2.36 square miles (6.11 km2), of which 0.012 square miles (0.03 km2), or 0.51%, are water.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The city sits on high ground that drains north to the Edwards River, a westward-flowing direct tributary of the Mississippi, and south to Pike Run, a tributary of Pope Creek, which flows to the Mississippi at Keithsburg.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] As of the 2020 census, Aledo had a population of 3,633.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] 21.7% of residents were under the age of 18 and 26.2% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] For every 100 females there were 91.6 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.5 males age 18 and over.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] 0.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 100.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] There were 1,559 households in Aledo, of which 26.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Of all households, 46.4% were married-couple households, 16.9% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 30.4% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] About 35.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 19.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] There were 1,749 housing units, of which 10.9% were vacant.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The homeowner vacancy rate was 4.3% and the rental vacancy rate was 13.8%.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] At the 2010 census, there were 3,640 people, 1,568 households and 947 families residing in the city.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 1.2% (45) of the population.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] There were 1,568 households, of which 24.5% had children under the age of 18 living in them, 49.0% were married couples living together, 3.6% had a male householder with no wife present, 7.8% had a female householder with no husband present and 39.6% were non-families.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] 35.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The average household size was 2.20 and the average family size was 2.84.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The 2009-2013 American Community Survey estimated the median household income in 2013 to be $39,424 and the median family income to be $56,546.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Full-time, year-round male workers were estimated to have a median income of $44,435 and females $30,357.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] About 15.0% of families and 18.4% of the population were estimated to be below the poverty line, including 22.1% of those under age 18 and 11.7% of those age 65 or over.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The American Community Survey estimated that in 2013 there were 1,740 civilians 16 years and over employed.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo was the home to William & Vashti College (1908–1917) — the campus/buildings were purchased and used by the Roosevelt Military Academy from 1924 to 1973.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The Administration Building was torn down, and the spot was used to construct an assisted living facility.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The remaining two buildings (Niles Hall and North Hall) are unused.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] William & Vashti College was a member of the Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference from 1910 to 1917.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The High School Mascot used to be the Aledo Green Dragons.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] School colors were Forest Green and White.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The Class of 2006 had 71 students, which is about an average class size.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Mercer County High School offers a variety of course curriculum in the sciences, math, literature, social sciences, and the arts.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The school has a concert band, jazz band, marching band, concert choir, and swing choir.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The school also offers a variety of athletics including volleyball, football, both men and women's golf, men and women's basketball, wrestling, track and field, softball, baseball, and cross country.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Some extracurricular activities that students can become involved in are scholastic bowl, football, basketball, pom poms, cheerleading, flags, majorettes, and musicals.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] From 1915 to 2009, Aledo High School competed in boys football.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] They qualified for the state tournament on 17 occasions since the tournament began in 1974.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] From 1998 to 2006, Aledo High School has reached the finals of five IHSA boys' football championship tournaments.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Of those five, the school won three times.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo School District #201 and Westmer School District #203 have consolidated since the 2009–2010 school year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The consolidation was voted upon by both school boards and was on the ballot for the 2008 election.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The new consolidated district is Mercer County District #404 and the new mascot adopted by popular vote in early 2009 is the Mercer County Golden Eagles.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] School colors changed to navy blue and vegas gold.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The Class of 2010 had over 120 students, well above the usual average.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo hosts two annual festivals, the Rhubarb Fest and Antique Days.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The Rhubarb Festival, which is held every June in the city downtown, offers a variety of rhubarb-related activities, ranging from rhubarb pie sales to free rhubarb seed distributions.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The festival additionally offers other crafts and forms of entertainment and music; it has been undertaken every year since 1991.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The city of Aledo's Antique Days festivals likewise occur annually in the month of September, and includes a citywide food festival, music from local residents and the high school music departments, and sports competitions among communities in the area.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Aledo has its own radio station, WRMJ-FM.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] WRMJ features country music along with live sports, local news and local programming.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] It broadcasts on a frequency of 102.3 MHz from a tower west of Aledo.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] The radio station serves most of Mercer County, and was founded in 1979.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] Mercer County's weekly newspaper, The *Times Record*, is based in Aledo and is owned by Gannett.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/aledo-illinois] *National Communications Magazine*, a publication for radio hobbyists, moved its operations from Ohio to Aledo in 2014 after being acquired by a local resident.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny College was founded in April 1815 by Timothy Alden, a graduate of Harvard's School of Divinity.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The college had been affiliated with the United Methodist Church from 1833 until the relationship was suspended in 2020, but has not integrated religion into the classroom or pedagogy.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The first class, consisting of four male students, began their studies on July 4, 1816, without any formal academic buildings.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Within six years, Alden accumulated sufficient funds to begin building a campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The first building erected, the library, was designed by Alden himself, and is a notable example of early American architecture.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Bentley Hall is named in honor of William Bentley, who donated his private library to the college, a collection of considerable value and significance.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In 1824, Thomas Jefferson wrote to Alden, expressing the hope that his University of Virginia could someday possess the richness of Allegheny's library.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Alden served as president of the college until 1831 when financial and enrollment difficulties forced his resignation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny began admitting women in 1870, early for a US college; a woman was valedictorian of the Allegheny class of 1875.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] By the time Ida Tarbell, future journalist, arrived in 1876, nineteen women had attended Allegheny and only two had graduated.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Tarbell described Ruter Hall in her writing, "...looking out on the town in the valley, its roofs and towers half hidden by a wealth of trees, and beyond it to a circle of round-breasted hills.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In 1905, Allegheny built Alden Hall as a new and improved preparatory school.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Over the decades, the college has grown in size and significance while still maintaining ties to the community.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In 1970, the film *Been Down So Long It Looks Like Up to Me* based on the Richard Fariña novel was filmed on college grounds.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] While the word "Allegheny" is a brand for the college, it is also the name of a county, a river, and a mountain range, and the school has tried to prevent other entities from using this word.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] For example, Allegheny objected in 2006 when Penn State tried to rename one of its campuses "Allegheny".
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny president Richard Cook said 'Allegheny' was "our brand." It sued the Philadelphia's Allegheny Health and Research Foundation in 1997 to change its name.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Mullen Jr. took office as the 21st president of Allegheny.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The college and the town cooperate in many ways.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] One study suggested the Allegheny College generates approximately $93 million annually into Meadville and the local economy.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny College's majors and minors fall into three spheres: Humanities, Natural Sciences, and Social Sciences.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There are some majors, such as Environmental Studies or International Studies, which fall into the interdisciplinary category.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The college requires students to choose a minor as well as a major and encourages "unusual combinations" of majors and minors.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] A student's major can be in the humanities, social sciences or natural sciences, but that student's minor must be in a different division than their major.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny is accredited by the Middle States Commission on Higher Education (MSCHE).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] About 30% of the college's 2,100 students graduate in one of the STEM disciplines—science, technology, engineering, and math.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Students must take at least two courses (8 semester credit hours) in a discipline other than their major or minor.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The most popular majors, in terms of 2021 graduates, were Biology/Biological Sciences (35), Psychology (34), and Environmental Science (33).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Total credits for graduation are 128 semester credit hours and no more than 64 credit hours can be from any one department.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Almost all courses carry four semester hours of credit.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The college requires all students to take a three-seminar series which "encourages careful listening and reading, thoughtful speaking and writing, and reflective academic planning and self-exploration," to be completed in their first two years.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Sophomores typically meet with faculty advisers eight times a year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny requires seniors to complete a *senior project* in their major.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Some senior projects can be quite ambitious; in 2007, one senior project involved comprehensive instructions for installing solar panels on the roof of a campus building.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny divides its academic calendar into two 15-week semesters.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The school year typically runs from the last week of August to mid-May, with a short fall break in mid-October, a Wednesday-to-Sunday Thanksgiving break, a month-long winter break from mid-December to mid-January, and a week-long spring break in the third week of March.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] It formerly had a Chinese language minor, which was discontinued with the Chinese program itself in 2022.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny offers direct enrollment programs at Lancaster University, England; James Cook University, Australia; University of Natal, South Africa; Capital Normal University, China; and Karl-Eberhard University, Germany.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] It also offers language and area studies programs in Seville, Spain; Angers, France; Karls-Eberhard University, Germany; and Querétaro, Mexico and internship programs in London, England; Paris, France; and Washington D.C.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny faculty members have led domestic summer-study tours to New York, Yellowstone, Austria, Costa Rica, and South Africa.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny has medical school cooperative programs available with three institutions: Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine, Drexel University and Jefferson Medical College.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny offers pre-professional programs in law and health.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] It has an arrangement with Drexel University College of Medicine to admit two Allegheny students who meet specific criteria (grades, MCAT scores).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] It has an arrangement with the William E.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Simon School of Business Administration at the University of Rochester to have preferred admission to selected students by the end of their junior year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny offers cooperative 3–2 liberal arts/professional programs in engineering with Case Western Reserve University, Columbia University, the University of Pittsburgh, and Washington University in St.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There is also a 3–2 Master of Information Systems Management (MISM) program reciprocal agreement with Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Four faculty won Fulbright Awards in March 2001.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Faculty sometimes focus on the local area; for example, economics professor Stephen Onyeiwu conducted a study of manufacturing in the northwestern Pennsylvania region.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Ninety percent of faculty have terminal degrees in their respective fields.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Books by faculty include *Congressional Women* and *Comedy from Shakespeare to Sheridan*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Faculty actively publish on a wide range of subjects from the biology of woodpeckers, to structural features of ribosomal RNA, to freshwater invertebrates.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In 2018, Professor Shannan Mattiace won a Fulbright Award to teach and conduct research in Chile.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There were 5,479 applications for admission to the class of 2022 (enrolling fall 2018): 3,485 were admitted (63.6%) and 474 enrolled (an admissions yield of 13.6%).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The average high school GPA of enrolled freshmen was 3.51, and 35% had a high school GPA of 3.75 or higher.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The middle 50% range of enrolled freshmen on SAT scores was 560–680 for reading and writing, and 560-660 for math, while the ACT Composite middle 50% range was 24–30.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Students generally are required to live on campus for all four years, and may reside in traditional dormitories, apartment-style housing, or college-owned houses.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The demographics of students as of fall 2015 were: White (non-Hispanic) 75.9%; Hispanic/Latino 7.0%, Black (non-Hispanic) 5.9%; Two or more races 4.7%, Non-resident alien 2.8%, Asian & Pacific Islander 2.4%; American Indian or Alaskan native 0.1%; Unknown 1.2% .
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny students in 2008 come from 33 states and 25 other countries.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny had a "diversity index" of .15 on a scale of .99=extremely diverse to .01=not diverse.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Students participate in volunteer activities: in the fall semester of 2011, the student body contributed 25,000 hours of volunteer service to the community.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Some Allegheny students volunteered to help restore businesses in hurricane-ravished New Orleans.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Residence halls and classrooms are closed during summers.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] An Allegheny Student Government has an active role in formulating college policy, curriculum choices, personal conduct, promoting cultural programs, and making decisions about the school's calendar.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Information about students is generally kept private in keeping with the 1974 "Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act" which prohibits colleges from releasing information about their students without student permission.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Accordingly, parents can not learn about their son's or daughter's grades unless a waiver is signed permitting release of such information.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The privacy policy can sometimes lead to problems, particularly when students have mental health problems but the school is prevented legally from contacting parents.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In 2002, one Allegheny student committed suicide, and his parents sued the school; a jury in 2006 found that the school was not liable or negligent.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] This case helped focus national attention on the competing issues of student privacy and parental rights.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Official college policy is to discourage underage drinking, although there have been incidents of violations at off-campus parties.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Incoming students are required to take an online course about the dangers of alcohol abuse.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The school punishes transgressions with disciplinary action.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Students run a campus radio station WARC 90.3 FM and a publication called "The Allegheny Review" of undergraduate literature.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny has numerous student groups and organizations such as an astronomy club, a College Choir, an Outing Club, and a Peace Coalition.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There are over 100 clubs and organizations offered at Allegheny.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The Allegheny newspaper is called *The Campus.* It is distributed weekly at locations all over the college.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] It covers campus news, features, opinion and a wrap-up of the college sports.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] *The Campus* is entirely student-run, with an editorial board of students in charge of making all executive decisions for the publication.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The Allegheny alternative magazine is called *Overkill.* It is tri-semester student publication distributed in unconventional locations around campus, such as in vending machines, fireplaces, and chandeliers.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] It features student editorials, poetry, non-fiction and fiction pieces, art, and photography with a highly distinctive design and attitude.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny has welcomed a variety of entertainers and guest speakers over the last several years including John Updike, Dave Matthews, Dick Cheney, Bill Clinton, W.D.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Snodgrass, Adam Sandler, George Carlin, The Vienna Choir Boys, Rusted Root, Ben Folds, The Roots, Stephen Lynch, The Fray, Jimmy Fallon, and comedian Wayne Brady.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There have been "live" art shows in which invited artists, over an eight-hour period, created 10-by-10-foot "drawings" on gallery walls while spectators watched.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny, known athletically as the Gators, belongs to the Presidents' Athletic Conference (PAC) and has NCAA Division III teams.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The Gators returned to the PAC in 2022 after a 38-year absence spent in the North Coast Athletic Conference (NCAC); the field hockey team remains in the NCAC because the PAC does not sponsor that sport.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Men's sports are baseball, basketball, cross country, football, golf, soccer, swimming and diving, tennis, and track & field.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Women's sports are basketball, cross country, golf, lacrosse, soccer, softball, swimming & diving, tennis, track & field, and volleyball.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Sports facilities include the Wise Center and the Robertson Complex.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] 75 percent of students play intramural sports.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Branch Rickey was Allegheny College Athletic Director from 1904 to 1905, and coached baseball, basketball, and football.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Rickey also served as instructor of Shakespeare, English, and History.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The 1990 Allegheny football team, led by first-year head coach Ken O'Keefe, won the Division III football national championship with a 13–0–1 record and a 21–14 victory over Lycoming in the Stagg Bowl.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny College has undertaken several projects to become more a sustainable campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] One such project is the October Energy Challenge, in which students are encouraged to save electricity for a one-month period.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The difference in cost between that month and the previous month's electrical power is then reinvested back into sustainable campus infrastructure.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Previous energy challenge have resulted in the addition of water-bottle stations to encourage use of reusable water bottles and solar panels on the biology building.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There are multiple student groups dedicated to environmental protection including SEA (Students for Environmental Action), AC Food Rescue, and Creek connections.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] One tradition is that a female student is not a "real co-ed" until she's been kissed on the *thirteenth plank* of the Rustic bridge over the stream.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Legend states that there is a competition among residence halls during Orientation Week to steal the thirteenth plank and display it, though this rarely happens today; random students take the plank instead, with maintenance keeping a supply of replacement planks on hand.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny College also has a number of fraternities and sororities on campus.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] These include Kappa Kappa Gamma, Kappa Alpha Theta, Delta Delta Delta, Alpha Delta Pi, and Alpha Chi Omega for the sororities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In 2009, 34% of Allegheny women belonged to a sorority.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny is located in northwestern Pennsylvania 90 miles (140 km) north of Pittsburgh, 90 miles (140 km) east of Cleveland, and 35 miles (56 km) south of Erie, in the town of Meadville, Pennsylvania.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The acting president since September 2022 is Ron Cole, the college's former provost and Dean of college.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] There are approximately 150 administration and staff personnel in 2008.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] In addition, part-time staff included 36 instructors, 23 other professionals, 10 secretaries, and 4 service and maintenance staff.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Of the 157 full-time faculty, 87 have tenure, and 41 are on a tenure track.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] The average salaries of professors (in 2007) was $83K, associate professors was $63K, assistant professors was $51K, instructors was $38K.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allegheny-college] Allegheny is a member of the Higher Education Data Sharing Consortium, or HEDS, in which member institutions share information relating to improvement of higher education.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Hubbell, found a specimen in the Como Bluff area, but apparently did not mention its completeness and Cope never unpacked it.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Upon unpacking it in 1903 (several years after Cope had died), it was found to be one of the most complete theropod specimens then known and the skeleton, now cataloged as AMNH 5753, was put on public view in 1908.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This is the well-known mount poised over a partial *Apatosaurus* skeleton as if scavenging it, illustrated as such in a painting by Charles R.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Although notable as the first free-standing mount of a theropod dinosaur and often illustrated and photographed, it has never been scientifically described.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The many names coined by Cope and Marsh complicated later research, with the situation further compounded by the terse descriptions they provided.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Even at the time, authors such as Samuel W.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Williston suggested that too many names had been coined.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] For example, Williston pointed out in 1901 that Marsh had never been able to adequately distinguish *Allosaurus* from *Creosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The most influential early attempt to sort out the situation was produced by Charles W.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] He came to the conclusion that the tail vertebra named *Antrodemus* by Leidy was indistinguishable from those of *Allosaurus* and that *Antrodemus* should be the preferred name because, as the older name, it had priority.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] *Antrodemus* became the accepted name for this familiar genus for over 50 years, until James H.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Madsen published on the Cleveland-Lloyd specimens and concluded that *Allosaurus* should be used because *Antrodemus* was based on material with poor, if any, diagnostic features and locality information.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] For example, the geological formation that the single bone of *Antrodemus* came from is unknown.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 1909, Earl Douglass from the Carnegie Museum discovered what should later become Dinosaur National Monument in Utah.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Until 2022, Douglass and his team excavated over 700,000 lb (320,000 kg) of fossils of multiple dinosaur species from a single quarry, including several *Allosaurus* specimens.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Among these finds is CM 11844, which was collected between 1913 and 1915 and comprises much of the skeleton and a fragmentary skull.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Since 1938, this skeleton is on display at the Carnegie Museum.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] During the summer of 1924, the University of Utah uncovered DINO 2560, the best preserved *Allosaurus* specimen known at that time.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The skull of this particularly large individual is on exhibit at the Dinosaur National Monument.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Although sporadic work at what became known as Utah's Cleveland-Lloyd Dinosaur Quarry had taken place as early as 1927 and the fossil site itself was described by William L.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Stokes in 1945, major operations did not begin there until 1960.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Madsen led a cooperative effort between 1960 and 1965 involving nearly 40 institutions, during which thousands of bones were recovered from the site.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The quarry is notable for the predominance of *Allosaurus* remains: the quarry preserves a minimum of 73 individual dinosaurs and at least 46 of those are *A. fragilis*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The great quantity of well-preserved *Allosaurus* remains has allowed this genus to be known in great detail, making it among the best-known of all theropods.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Skeletal remains from the quarry pertain to individuals of almost all ages and sizes, from less than 1 metre (3.3 feet) to 12 metres (39 feet) long.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Because its fossils are common at both this quarry and others in the state, *Allosaurus* was designated as the state fossil of Utah in 1988.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In the early 1990s, a Swiss team led by Kirby Siber set out for commercial fossil excavations at Howe Ranch Quarry, Wyoming.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This quarry had originally been worked on in 1934 by Barnum Brown and his crew, who collected more than 30 tons of bones, mostly of sauropods.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Because the Swiss team could not locate additional specimens in the quarry, they explored the surrounding area, where they discovered "Big Al" (MOR 693) in 1991: a 95% complete, partially articulated *Allosaurus* specimen.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, because the new site was located on public land, the excavation was taken over by a joint Museum of the Rockies and University of Wyoming Geological Museum team.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The specimen, now on exhibit at the Museum of the Rockies, belonged to an individual of about 8 m (26 ft) in length.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This was below the average size for *Allosaurus*, as it was a subadult estimated at only 87% grown.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The Swiss team later excavated a second *Allosaurus*, "Big Al II" (SMA 0005), on private land on Howe Ranch, which is exhibited at the Aathal Dinosaur Museum in Switzerland.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 1991, Brooks Britt argued that there were at least two species of *Allosaurus*: A robust species with a short and high skull and pointed lacrimal horns, and a more gracile species with a long and low skull and rounded lacrimal horns.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The robust species is geologically younger from localities such as Dry Mesa Quarry and Garden Park, while the gracile species, found at the Cleveland-Lloyd and at Dinosaur National Monument, is older.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Paul made a similar distinction in a popular book, in which he referred to the gracile species as *A. fragilis* and to the robust species as *A. atrox*, using a species originally described by Marsh as *Creosaurus atrox*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, a series of statistical analyses by David K.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Smith between 1996 and 1999 suggested that the differences seen in the Morrison Formation material can be attributed to individual variation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 2006, Octávio Mateus and colleagues reported a partial skull and three neck vertebrae (ML 415) from the Vale Frades beach in Lourinhã.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] As this specimen differed from North American *Allosaurus* fossils, they assigned it to a new species, *A. europaeus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] These authors also assigned the Andrés specimen to this species, though solely based on the fact that it was found in Portugal.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The presence of a separate *Allosaurus* species in Europe would suggest that faunal interchange between the continents was interrupted, possibly due to the opening of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The status of *A. europaeus* was controversially discussed in the subsequent years, with different studies arguing that the species is a synonym of *A. fragilis*, a *nomen dubium* (doubtful name), or in need of re-evaluation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 2024, André Burigo and Mateus re-described the Vale Frades specimen and carried out further fossil preparation that exposed additional bones.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] These authors identified nine unique features supporting the validity *A. europaeus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A 2025 study by Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues described the Andrés specimens in detail, including a newly discovered set of skull bones.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Their analysis of the relationships between individual *Allosaurus* skulls instead suggested that *A. europaeus* is a synonym of *A. fragilis* because the Andrés specimens were more closely related to some North American specimens than to the Vale Frades specimen.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] On July 15, 1990, George Engelmann discovered toe bones and some tail vertebrae weathering out of the rock while conducting an inventory of fossils at Dinosaur National Monument.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Staff of the National Monument began excavating the new specimen later that year; the conditions were difficult because of its location in a steeply inclined rock face that, with ongoing excavation, became vertical.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 1994, much of the excavated skeleton was flown out via helicopter in single block weighing 2,700 kg (6,000 lb).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The skull, which was still missing, was only located two years later, in 1996, with the help of novel radiological surveying techniques that detect gamma radiation from radioactive minerals which accumulate in bones during fossilization.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The specimen, DINO 11541, is one of the most complete theropod skeletons recovered from the Late Jurassic.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 2000, Daniel Chure described the specimen in his PhD thesis, arguing that it represents a new species, *A. jimmadseni*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, as the thesis did not meet the requirements of the International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature (ICZN), it remained an invalid *nomen nudum* ("naked name") until Chure and Mark Loewen formally described the species in 2020.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] These authors assigned several other specimens to *A. jimmadseni*, including the original "Big Al" individual (MOR 693).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The name *jimmadseni* honors Madsen for his contributions to the taxonomy of the genus, notably his 1976 work.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The issue of species and potential synonyms was historically complicated by the type specimen of *Allosaurus fragilis* (YPM 1930) being extremely fragmentary.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Because of this, several scientists have interpreted the type specimen as potentially dubious, meaning the genus *Allosaurus* itself or at least the species *A. fragilis* would be a *nomen dubium* ("dubious name", based on a specimen too incomplete to compare to other specimens or to classify).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Paul and Kenneth Carpenter submitted a petition to the ICZN in 2010 to have the more complete specimen USNM 4734 selected as a neotype, a decision that was ratified by the ICZN on December 29, 2023.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 2014, Sebastian Dalman named the new species *Allosaurus lucasi* based on two specimens from the Tithonian of Colorado, but this species was not accepted by later authors.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In 1995, Chure created the taxon *Saurophaganax maximus* for giant allosaurid remains from western Oklahoma.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] These remains had been known as *Saurophagus*, but that name was already in use, leading Chure to propose a substitute.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Smith, in his 1998 analysis of variation, concluded that *S. maximus* was not different enough from *Allosaurus* to be a separate genus, but did warrant its own species, *A. maximus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This reassignment was rejected in a review of basal tetanurans.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A 2024 reassessment by Andy Danison and colleagues suggested that the *Saurophaganax* specimen is a chimera that combines the bones of *Allosaurus* with those of a sauropod.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The holotype of *Saurophaganax* itself, a neural arch, cannot be confidently be assigned to a theropod, making it a *nomen dubium*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The *Allosaurus* bones, however, were found to be distinct enough to warrant a new species of *Allosaurus*, *A. anax*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The name *anax* is Greek for 'king', and also alludes to the name change from *Saurophagus* to *Saurophaganax*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Several gigantic specimens have been attributed to *Allosaurus*, but may in fact belong to other genera .
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The dubious genus *Saurophaganax* (OMNH 1708) was estimated to reach around 10.5 m (34 ft) in length, and its single species has sometimes been included in the genus *Allosaurus* as *A. maximus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, a 2024 study questioned the referral of materials beyond the holotype to *Saurophaganax*, with the material they could confidently assign to Allosauridae belonging to the new species *Allosaurus anax*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The body mass of this species was estimated around 3.8–4.6 metric tons (4.2–5.1 short tons) based on fragmentary material.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Another potential specimen of *Allosaurus*, once assigned to the genus *Epanterias* (AMNH 5767), may have measured 12.1 m (40 ft) in length.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A more recent discovery is a partial skeleton from the Peterson Quarry in Morrison rocks of New Mexico; this large allosaurid was suggested to be a potential specimen of *Saurophaganax* prior to this taxon's 2024 reassessment.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Smith, examining *Allosaurus* fossils by quarry, found that specimens from Utah's Cleveland-Lloyd Dinosaur Quarry are generally smaller than those from Wyoming's Como Bluff or the BYU Dry Mesa Quarry in Colorado, but the shapes of the bones themselves did not vary between the sites.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A later study by Smith incorporating specimens from the Garden Park and Dinosaur National Monument sites found no justification for multiple species based on skeletal variation; skull variation was most common and was gradational, suggesting individual variation was responsible.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Further work on size-related variation again found no consistent differences, although the Dry Mesa material tended to clump together on the basis of the astragalus, an ankle bone.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The skull of *Allosaurus* was light and equipped with dozens of sharp, serrated teeth, and both were modestly proportioned for a theropod of its size.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Paul gives a length of 845 mm (33.3 in) for a skull belonging to an individual he estimates at 7.9 m (26 ft) long.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Each premaxilla (the bones that formed the tip of the snout) held five teeth with D-shaped cross-sections, and each maxilla (the main tooth-bearing bones in the upper jaw) had between 14 and 17 teeth; the number of teeth does not exactly correspond to the size of the bone.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Each dentary (the tooth-bearing bone of the lower jaw) had between 14 and 17 teeth, with an average count of 16.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The teeth became shorter, narrower, and more curved toward the back of the skull.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] They were shed easily and continually replaced, making them common fossils.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The lacrimal bones of *Allosaurus* extend above and in front of the eyes to form a pair of horns which varied in shape and size.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Leading into the horns, the skull also features a pair of ridges running along the top of the nasal bones.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The horns were probably covered in a keratin sheath and may have had a variety of functions, including acting as sunshades for the eyes, being used for display, and being used in combat against other members of the same species (although they were fragile).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] There was a ridge along the back of the skull roof for muscle attachment, as is also seen in tyrannosaurids.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Inside the lacrimal bones were depressions that may have held glands, such as salt glands.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Within the maxillae were sinuses that were better developed than those of more basal theropods such as *Ceratosaurus* and *Marshosaurus*; they may have been related to the sense of smell, perhaps holding something like Jacobson's organs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The roof of the braincase was thin, perhaps to improve thermoregulation for the brain.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The skull and lower jaws had joints that permitted motion within these units.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In the lower jaws, the bones of the front and back halves loosely articulated, permitting the jaws to bow outward and increasing the animal's gape.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The braincase and frontals may also have had a joint.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The forelimbs of *Allosaurus* were short in comparison to the hindlimbs (only about 35% the length of the hindlimbs in adults) and had three fingers per hand, tipped with large, strongly curved and pointed claws.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The arms were powerful, and the forearm was somewhat shorter than the upper arm (1:1.2 ulna/humerus ratio).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The wrist had a version of the semilunate carpal also found in more derived theropods like maniraptorans.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Of the three fingers, the innermost (or thumb) was the largest, and diverged from the others.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The phalangeal formula is 2-3-4-0-0, meaning that the innermost finger (phalange) has two bones, the next has three, and the third finger has four.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The legs were not as long or suited for speed as those of tyrannosaurids, and the claws of the toes were less developed and more hoof-like than those of earlier theropods.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Each foot had three weight-bearing toes and an inner dewclaw, which Madsen suggested could have been used for grasping in juveniles.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] There was also what is interpreted as the splint-like remnant of a fifth (outermost) metatarsal, perhaps used as a lever between the Achilles tendon and foot.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A 2020 study by Motani and colleagues suggests that *Allosaurus* was also sexually dimorphic in the width of the femur's head against its length.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Skin impressions from *Allosaurus* have been described.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] One impression, from a juvenile specimen, measures 30 square centimeters and is associated with the anterior dorsal ribs/pectoral region.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The impression shows small scales measuring 1 to 3 millimeters in diameter.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A skin impression from the "Big Al Two" specimen, associated with the base of the tail, measures 20 centimeters by 20 centimeters and shows large scales measuring up to 2 centimeters in diameter.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, it has been noted that these scales are more similar to those of sauropods, and due to the presence of non-theropod remains associated with the tail of "Big Al Two" there is a possibility that this skin impression is not from *Allosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Another *Allosaurus* fossil features a skin impression from the mandible, showing scales measuring 1 to 2 millimeters in diameter.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The same fossil also preserves skin measuring 20 by 20 centimeters from the ventral side of the neck, showing scutate scales measuring 0.5 centimeters wide and 11 centimeters long.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A small skin impression from an *Allosaurus* skull has been reported but never described.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Additional undescribed skin impressions are known from various parts of the body in one specimen.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Together with the group Carcharodontosauria, Allosauridae is often classified within the group Allosauria.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Allosauria, in turn, forms the group Allosauroidea together with the family Metriacanthosauridae in many analyses.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Historically, *Allosaurus* has often been classified in the group Carnosauria, which originally encompassed any large theropod that was not a ceratosaur or a tyrannosaurid.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Carnosauria is still sometimes used, either to encompass the groups Allosauroidea and Megalosauroidea, or as an approximate synonym of Allosauroidea.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Paul used the subfamily Allosaurinae to unite the genera *Allosaurus* and *Chilantaisaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The wealth of *Allosaurus* fossils, from nearly all ages of individuals, allows scientists to study how the animal grew and how long its lifespan may have been.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Remains may reach as far back in the lifespan as eggs—crushed eggs from Colorado have been suggested as those of *Allosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Based on histological analysis of limb bones, bone deposition appears to stop at around 22 to 28 years, which is comparable to that of other large theropods like *Tyrannosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] From the same analysis, its maximum growth appears to have been at age 15, with an estimated growth rate of about 148 kilograms (326 lb) per year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Medullary bone tissue (endosteally derived, ephemeral, mineralization located inside the medulla of the long bones in gravid female birds) has been reported in at least one *Allosaurus* specimen, a shin bone from the Cleveland-Lloyd Quarry.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Today, this bone tissue is only formed in female birds that are laying eggs, as it is used to supply calcium to shells.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Its presence in the *Allosaurus* individual has been used to establish sex and show it had reached reproductive age.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, other studies have called into question some cases of medullary bone in dinosaurs, including this *Allosaurus* individual.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Data from extant birds suggested that the medullary bone in this *Allosaurus* individual may have been the result of a bone pathology instead.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, with the confirmation of medullary tissue indicating sex in a specimen of *Tyrannosaurus*, it may be possible to ascertain whether or not the *Allosaurus* in question was indeed female.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The discovery of SDSM 30510, a juvenile specimen with a nearly complete hindlimb shows that the legs were relatively longer in juveniles, and the lower segments of the leg (shin and foot) were relatively longer than the thigh.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] These differences suggest that like the much later-living tyrannosaurids, younger *Allosaurus* were faster and filled separate predatory niches than adults, perhaps being cursorial predators of smaller prey as juveniles before becoming ambush hunters of large prey as they matured.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The thigh bone became thicker and wider during growth, and the cross-section less circular, as muscle attachments shifted, muscles became shorter, and the growth of the leg slowed.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] These changes imply that juvenile legs has less predictable stresses compared with adults, which would have moved with more regular forward progression.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Conversely, the skull bones appear to have generally grown isometrically, increasing in size without changing in proportion.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Most paleontologists accept *Allosaurus* as an active predator of large animals.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Sauropods seem to be likely candidates as both live prey and as objects of scavenging, based on the presence of scrapings on sauropod bones fitting allosaur teeth well and the presence of shed allosaur teeth with sauropod bones.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] However, as Gregory Paul noted in 1988, *Allosaurus* was probably not a predator of fully grown sauropods, unless it hunted in packs, as it had a modestly sized skull and relatively small teeth, and was greatly outweighed by contemporaneous sauropods.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Another possibility is that it preferred to hunt juveniles instead of fully grown adults.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Research in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century may have found other solutions to this question.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Bakker, comparing *Allosaurus* to Cenozoic saber-toothed carnivorous mammals, found similar adaptations, such as a reduction of jaw muscles and increase in neck muscles, and the ability to open the jaws extremely wide.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Although *Allosaurus* did not have saber teeth, Bakker suggested another mode of attack that would have used such neck and jaw adaptations: the short teeth in effect became small serrations on a saw-like cutting edge running the length of the upper jaw, which would have been driven into prey.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This type of jaw would permit slashing attacks against much larger prey, with the goal of weakening the victim.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Similar conclusions were drawn by another study using finite element analysis on an *Allosaurus* skull.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] According to their biomechanical analysis, the skull was very strong but had a relatively small bite force.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] By using jaw muscles only, it could produce a bite force of 805 to 8,724 N, but the skull could withstand nearly 55,500 N of vertical force against the tooth row.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The authors suggested that *Allosaurus* used its skull like a machete against prey, attacking open-mouthed, slashing flesh with its teeth, and tearing it away without splintering bones, unlike *Tyrannosaurus*, which is thought to have been capable of damaging bones.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Their interpretations were challenged by other researchers, who found no modern analogs to a hatchet attack and considered it more likely that the skull was strong to compensate for its open construction when absorbing the stresses from struggling prey.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The original authors noted that *Allosaurus* itself has no modern equivalent, that the tooth row is well-suited to such an attack, and that articulations in the skull cited by their detractors as problematic actually helped protect the palate and lessen stress.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Another possibility for handling large prey is that theropods like *Allosaurus* were "flesh grazers" which could take bites of flesh out of living sauropods that were sufficient to sustain the predator so it would not have needed to expend the effort to kill the prey outright.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This strategy would also potentially have allowed the prey to recover and be fed upon in a similar way later.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This is compatible with other evidence that the forelimbs were strong and capable of restraining prey.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Studies done by Stephen Lautenschager et al. from the University of Bristol also indicate *Allosaurus* could open its jaws quite wide and sustain considerable muscle force.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] When compared with *Tyrannosaurus* and the therizinosaurid *Erlikosaurus* in the same study, it was found that *Allosaurus* had a wider gape than either; the animal was capable of opening its jaws to a 92-degree angle at maximum.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The findings also indicate that large carnivorous dinosaurs, like modern carnivores, had wider jaw gapes than herbivores.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A biomechanical study published in 2013 by Eric Snively and colleagues found that *Allosaurus* had an unusually low attachment point on the skull for the longissimus capitis superficialis neck muscle compared to other theropods such as *Tyrannosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This would have allowed the animal to make rapid and forceful vertical movements with the skull.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The authors found that vertical strikes as proposed by Bakker and Rayfield are consistent with the animal's capabilities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] They also found that the animal probably processed carcasses by vertical movements in a similar manner to falcons, such as kestrels: The animal could have gripped prey with the skull and feet, then pulled back and up to remove flesh.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This differs from the prey-handling envisioned for tyrannosaurids, which probably tore flesh with lateral shakes of the skull, similar to crocodilians.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] In addition, *Allosaurus* was able to "move its head and neck around relatively rapidly and with considerable control", at the cost of power.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Other aspects of feeding include the eyes, arms, and legs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The shape of the skull of *Allosaurus* limited potential binocular vision to 20° of width, slightly less than that of modern crocodilians.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] As with crocodilians, this may have been enough to judge prey distance and time attacks.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The arms, compared with those of other theropods, were suited for both grasping prey at a distance or clutching it close, and the articulation of the claws suggests that they could have been used to hook things.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Finally, the top speed of *Allosaurus* has been estimated at 30–55 km (19–34 mi) per hour.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Sauropod carrion may also have been important to large theropods in the Morrison Formation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Forensic techniques indicate that sauropod carcasses were targeted by *Allosaurus* at all stages of decomposition, indicating that late-stage decay pathogens were not a significant deterrent.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A single dead adult *Barosaurus* or *Brachiosaurus* would have had enough calories to sustain multiple large theropods for weeks or months, though the vast majority of the Morrison's sauropod fossil record consisted of much smaller-bodied taxa such as *Camarasaurus lentus* or *Diplodocus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] It has been speculated since the 1970s that *Allosaurus* preyed on sauropods and other large dinosaurs by hunting in groups.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Such a depiction is common in semitechnical and popular dinosaur literature.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Bakker has extended social behavior to parental care, and has interpreted shed allosaur teeth and chewed bones of large prey animals as evidence that adult allosaurs brought food to lairs for their young to eat until they were grown, and prevented other carnivores from scavenging on the food.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Such head-biting may have been a way to establish dominance in a pack or to settle territorial disputes.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This could explain the high proportion of juvenile and subadult allosaurs present, as juveniles and subadults are disproportionally killed at modern group feeding sites of animals like crocodiles and Komodo dragons.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The same interpretation applies to Bakker's lair sites.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] There is some evidence for cannibalism in *Allosaurus*, including *Allosaurus* shed teeth found among rib fragments, possible tooth marks on a shoulder blade, and cannibalized allosaur skeletons among the bones at Bakker's lair sites.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Pathological analysis done by Foth *et al.* argued that evidence of surviving serious injuries may support gregariousness in *Allosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The brain of *Allosaurus*, as interpreted from spiral CT scanning of an endocast, was more consistent with crocodilian brains than those of the other living archosaurs, birds.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The structure of the vestibular apparatus indicates that the skull was held nearly horizontal, as opposed to strongly tipped up or down.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The structure of the inner ear was like that of a crocodilian, indicating that *Allosaurus* was more adapted to hear lower frequencies and would have had difficulty hearing subtle sounds.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The olfactory bulbs were large and well suited for detecting odors, but were typical for an animal of its size.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The opening for the trigeminal nerve was relatively small compared to those of birds and crocodilians; this is also true of other non-avian theropods, and suggests they did not have the heightened facial sensitivity of crocodilians and some birds.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] As with other large theropods, the endocranial volume of *Allosaurus* is proportionally greater than in smaller theropods; this is thought to have accommodated larger dural venous sinuses, helping to cool the brain.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The specimen "Big Al" is well-known for its numerous injuries.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Nineteen of its bones were broken or showed signs of serious infection, which may have contributed to "Big Al's" death.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Pathologic bones included five ribs, five vertebrae, and four bones of the feet.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A particular problem for the living animal was infection and trauma to the right foot that probably affected movement and may have also predisposed the other foot to injury because of a change in gait.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] "Big Al" had an infection on the first phalanx on the third toe that was afflicted by an involucrum.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The infection was long-lived, perhaps up to six months.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The left scapula and fibula of an *Allosaurus fragilis* specimen cataloged as USNM 4734 are both pathological, both probably due to healed fractures.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] The specimen USNM 8367 preserved several pathological gastralia which preserve evidence of healed fractures near their middle.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Some of the fractures were poorly healed and "formed pseudoarthroses".
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] A specimen with a fractured rib was recovered from the Cleveland-Lloyd Quarry.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Another specimen had fractured ribs and fused vertebrae near the end of the tail.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] An apparent subadult male *Allosaurus fragilis* was reported to have extensive pathologies, with a total of fourteen separate injuries.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] Additionally, a subadult *Allosaurus* individual that suffered from spondyloarthropathy has been discovered in Dana Quarry in Wyoming.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p01] This finding represents the first known fossil evidence of spondyloarthropathy occurring in a theropod.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] The Morrison Formation covers an area of 1.2 million km², and *Allosaurus* is found across this range.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] It occurs in the Salt Wash and Brushy Basin members and their equivalents, being absent only in the oldest part of the formation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] Most specimens are not yet assigned to any particular species.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] According to a 2024 study by Susannah Maidment, *A. fragilis* and *A. jimmadseni* appear to have been contemporaneous but separated geographically, with *A. fragilis* concentrated in the south and east of the Morrison basin and *A. jimmadseni* in the north and west.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] Both species occur together only at Dry Mesa quarry.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] The species *A. anax* is only known from the Kenton 1 Quarry in western Oklahoma from rocks of the Kenton Member, a locally recognised member equivalent to the Brushy Basin Member.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] *Allosaurus* is the most common theropod in the Morrison Formation, accounting for 70 to 75% of theropod specimens.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] The Morrison Formation is interpreted as a semiarid environment with distinct wet and dry seasons, and flat floodplains.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] Vegetation varied from river-lining forests of conifers, tree ferns, and ferns (gallery forests), to fern savannas with occasional trees such as the *Araucaria*-like conifer *Brachyphyllum*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] *Allosaurus* is commonly found at the same sites as *Apatosaurus*, *Camarasaurus*, *Diplodocus*, and *Stegosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] The Late Jurassic formations of Portugal where *Allosaurus* is present are interpreted as having been similar to the Morrison, but with a stronger marine influence.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] Many of the dinosaurs of the Morrison Formation are the same genera as those seen in Portuguese rocks (mainly *Allosaurus*, *Ceratosaurus*, *Torvosaurus*, and *Stegosaurus*), or have a close counterpart (*Brachiosaurus* and *Lusotitan*, *Camptosaurus* and *Draconyx*).
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] Utah's Cleveland-Lloyd quarry is unusual in that about 66% of the vertebrate fossils belong to a single species of carnivore, *A. fragilis*, and that the bones are *disarticulated* (no longer connected to each other) and well-mixed.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] More papers have been published on how this site may have formed than on any other fossil tetrapod site.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] A popular idea is that the site was a predator trap to which the *Allosaurus* were attracted and became mired.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] In this case, the carcasses could have accumulated over a longer period of time.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] Other studies postulated a single catastrophe as the cause, such as a severe drought during which an *Allosaurus* population congregated around a water hole and, by their presence, deterred other dinosaurs.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] The disarticulation of the bones has been explained with trampling by other dinosaurs; movements of the sediment; scavenging; up-welling water; or repeated reworking and re-deposition of the bones.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] It is also possible that the *Allosaurus* population died elsewhere for unknown reasons and that their bones were washed into the site.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] A bone assemblage in the Upper Jurassic Mygatt-Moore Quarry preserves an unusually high occurrence of theropod bite marks, most of which can be attributed to *Allosaurus* and *Ceratosaurus*, while others could have been made by *Torvosaurus* given the size of the striations.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] While the position of the bite marks on the herbivorous dinosaurs is consistent with predation or early access to remains, bite marks found on *Allosaurus* material suggest scavenging, either from the other theropods or from another *Allosaurus*.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/allosaurus-p02] The unusually high concentration of theropod bite marks compared to other assemblages could be explained either by a more complete utilization of resources during a dry season by theropods, or by a collecting bias in other localities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Augustana College was founded as Augustana College and Theological Seminary in 1860 by the Scandinavian Evangelical Lutheran Augustana Synod.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Located first in Chicago, it moved to Paxton, Illinois, in 1863 and to Rock Island, Illinois, its current home, in 1875.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] After 1890, an increasingly large Swedish American community in America promoted a new institutional structure, including a lively Swedish-language press, many new churches, several colleges, and a network of ethnic organizations.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The result was to foster a sense of Swedishness with pride in the United States.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Thus, there emerged a self-confident Americanized generation.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Augustana College put itself in the lead of the movement to affirm Swedish American identity.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Early on all the students had been born in Sweden but by 1890 the second generation of American-born students predominated.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] They typically had white-collar or professional backgrounds; few were the sons and daughters of farmers and laborers.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] These middle class youth developed an idealized view of Sweden, characterized by romanticism, patriotism, and idealism, just like their counterparts across the Atlantic.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The new generation was especially proud of the Swedish contributions to American democracy and of the creation of a republic that promised liberty and destroyed the menace of slavery.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The college grew by donation of 5 acres (2.0 ha) on the south in 1886 and purchase, enabled by donation of C.J.A.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Ericson, of 10–12 acres to the north in 1899.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] In 1947, when Conrad Bergendoff was college president, the Augustana Seminary formally separated from Augustana College and became an independent body.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] It remained on the Rock Island campus until the 1960s, when the seminary moved to Chicago.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] It merged with other Lutheran seminaries to form the Lutheran School of Theology at Chicago.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Old Main was constructed between 1884 and 1893.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] It is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] On August 2, 2010, the New Science Building was officially named the Robert A. and Patricia K.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Hanson Hall of Science after Robert Hanson, a former John Deere CEO.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Hanson, who donated $8 million to the college, credits his success in life to his time spent at Augustana.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The science building, dedicated in 1998 and enlarged in 2019, is the largest academic building serving approximately 700 students in 17 majors, minors and concentrations.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] In October 2021, Augustana dedicated the Peter J.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Lindberg, M.D., Center for Health and Human Performance in honor of alumnus Peter J.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The 52,000-square-foot Lindberg Center is home to the college's new kinesiology program and growing public health program, as well as the men's and women's swimming/diving and new water polo teams.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Augustana has five traditional residence halls: Andreen Hall, Erickson Residence Center, Seminary Hall, Swanson Commons, and Westerlin Residence Center.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] All five of these residence halls are coeducational.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The majority of first-year and sophomore-year students typically reside in one of these five residence halls.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] For juniors, Augustana also offers Transitional Living Areas (TLAs), apartment-like complexes or traditional off-campus houses administered by the college's Office of Residential Life.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] These areas usually have 2–6 students who share a bathroom, a kitchen, and other living spaces.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The Fryxell Geology Museum, named after Augustana geologist Fritiof Fryxell, features a large collection of dinosaurs and fossils, rocks and mineral specimens.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Displays include a complete skeleton of a Platecarpus "sea serpent", skulls of Parasaurolophus, Ankylosaurus, Apatosaurus, Allosaurus and Tyrannosaurus rex and a 2-billion-year-old fossil.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] There is also a complete 22-foot-long (6.7 m) skeleton of Cryolophosaurus, a large, crested carnivorous dinosaur discovered in Antarctica in 1991 by Augustana paleontologist William Hammer.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The museum is located in the Swenson Hall of Geosciences.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] News & World Report*, the college was tied at 96 among "National Liberal Arts Colleges".
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Since 1950, Augustana has had a chapter of the Phi Beta Kappa honor society.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The college also has non-"Greek" collegiate fraternal organizations, including Epsilon Tau Pi (ΕΤΠ)(Eagle Scouts), Alpha Phi Omega (APO) (service), Sigma Alpha Iota (SAI) (music), Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia (PMA) (music), Epsilon Sigma Alpha (ESA) (Service), Alpha Psi Omega (ΑΨΩ) (theater), and others.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The Omicron chapter of Phrateres, a non-exclusive, non-profit social-service club, was installed here in 1941.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Between 1924 and 1967, 23 chapters of Phrateres were installed in universities across North America.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Augustana has eleven social Greek groups, six sororities and five fraternities.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Augustana College is located on the east side of Rock Island and is accessible via the Quad Cities MetroLINK.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Routes 10, 53, and 57 provide bus service from campus to downtown Rock Island, downtown Moline and other destinations.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Augustana athletic teams are nicknamed as the Vikings.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The college is a member of the Division III level of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA), primarily competing in the College Conference of Illinois and Wisconsin (CCIW) for almost all of their sports since the 1946–47 academic year.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The only current exception is women's bowling, in which the Vikings are charter members of the single-sport Central Intercollegiate Bowling Conference (CIBC) that began competition in the 2019–20 season.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The Vikings compete in a combined total of 25 male and female team sports, and five out of seven students compete in some form of varsity, club, or intramural sport.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] The Vikings previously competed as a member of the Illinois Intercollegiate Athletic Conference (IIAC) from 1912–13 to 1936–37.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Between 1983 and 1986, the Augustana College football team won four consecutive Division III national championships under Coach Bob Reade.
[src:augustana-college-illinois/augustana-college-illinois] Coach Reade's overall winning percentage of 87% is second only to Larry Kehres and Knute Rockne on the all-time list.
